Make GPT-OSS-20B run closer to tt-metal on Galaxy.

Target hardware/layout:
- Galaxy mesh is 4x8
- Treat mesh columns (size 8) as the tensor-parallel axis
- Treat mesh rows (size 4) as the extra distributed axis
- In tt-metal:
  - Decode uses TP=8 across columns and EP=4 across rows
  - Prefill uses TP=8 across columns and SP=4 across rows
- I care primarily about DECODE, especially batch size 128 on 4x8

Important high-level point:
- Matching weight shard specs alone is NOT enough
- tt-metal batch-128 decode on 4x8 also changes runtime execution:
  - users are row-sharded
  - MoE uses a throughput-experts path
  - tokens are redistributed with all_to_all dispatch/combine
  - expert outputs are then reduced across TP columns

GPT-OSS-20B config values:
- hidden_size = 2880
- intermediate_size = 2880
- num_attention_heads = 64
- num_key_value_heads = 8
- head_dim = 64
- num_local_experts = 32
- num_experts_per_tok = 4
- vocab_size = 201088
- num_hidden_layers = 24

How tt-metal parallelizes weights:
- Most ordinary model weight tensors are sharded over the 8 mesh columns, not over the 4 rows
- The 4 rows are mainly used for:
  - EP in decode
  - SP in prefill
  - user/page-table/KV row sharding when enabled
- For decode batch 128 on 4x8, local batch is 32 per row, but execution is NOT equivalent to simple 1x8 batch 32 because the MoE path is different

Closest tt-metal-style shard specs for HF weights:
- q_proj.weight -> ("model", None)
- k_proj.weight -> ("model", None)
- v_proj.weight -> ("model", None)
- o_proj.weight -> (None, "model")
- sinks -> ("model",)

- router.weight -> (None, None)

- experts.gate_up_proj -> (None, None, "model")
- experts.gate_up_proj_bias -> (None, "model")
- experts.down_proj -> (None, "model", None)
- experts.down_proj_bias -> safest approximation is replicate: (None, None)

Important caveat:
- tt-metal does special handling for some biases, especially down_proj_bias
- It is not just a raw HF tensor shard
- If exact transformed bias layout is hard to reproduce, replication is safer than incorrect sharding

Shapes on GPT-OSS-20B with model axis = 8 columns:
- q_proj.weight: [4096, 2880] -> local [512, 2880]
- k_proj.weight: [512, 2880] -> local [64, 2880]
- v_proj.weight: [512, 2880] -> local [64, 2880]
- o_proj.weight: [2880, 4096] -> local [2880, 512]
- sinks: [64] -> local [8]
- router.weight: [32, 2880] replicated
- gate_up_proj: [32, 2880, 5760] -> local [32, 2880, 720]
- gate_up_proj_bias: [32, 5760] -> local [32, 720]
- down_proj: [32, 2880, 2880] -> local [32, 360, 2880]
- down_proj_bias: [32, 2880] special-case in tt-metal
- embed_tokens.weight: [201088, 2880] replicated
- norm.weight: [2880] replicated
- lm_head.weight is transposed and padded before sharding in tt-metal:
  - raw HF shape [201088, 2880]
  - tt-metal loaded form is effectively [2880, padded_vocab]
  - vocab is padded before TP sharding for on-device sampling

Critical decode behavior on 4x8, batch 128:
- users_row_sharded = True
- global batch 128 is split across 4 rows => 32 users per row
- tt-metal uses throughput experts for multi-row + batch > 1
- this means decode is not just “same as 1x8 with bigger batch”

New decode ops on 4x8 batch 128 that matter:
- all_to_all_dispatch
- expert compute on dispatched tokens
- all_to_all_combine
- apply router weights and reduce across top-k experts
- all_reduce across TP columns

Interpretation of those ops:
- all_to_all_dispatch = send token work to the row/device that should process the selected experts
- all_to_all_combine = send expert outputs back to the original token owner
- final all_reduce across columns = merge TP partial outputs

What EP=4 means in tt-metal:
- EP=4 does NOT mean raw expert weights are simply sharded from 32 experts down to 8 experts per row in the plain tensor layout
- Raw expert axis in the regular expert tensors still appears as 32
- EP is realized mainly through runtime routing/distribution/combination across the 4 mesh rows
- Router still scores all 32 experts
- Runtime routing remaps/distributes expert work across rows

Decode comparison:
- 1x8 batch 32 and 4x8 batch 128 have similar per-row local batch size (32), but they are NOT equivalent globally
- Attention TP-local compute can look similar per row
- Full MoE decode behavior differs because 4x8 batch 128 adds row-sharded users plus throughput-experts dispatch/combine

What to implement in tt-xla if the goal is “more like tt-metal”:
1. Fix static shard specs to match the list above
2. Make logical model axis correspond to TP over 8 columns, not all 32 devices
3. For decode batch 128 on 4x8:
   - shard users/batch across the 4 rows
   - preserve TP over the 8 columns
   - add MoE token redistribution semantics equivalent to dispatch/combine
   - add the final TP-column reduction after expert outputs
4. Do not assume that weight sharding alone reproduces tt-metal behavior
5. If exact throughput-experts path is too large to implement immediately, first match:
   - correct weight sharding
   - row-sharded batch/users
   - correct router/top-k semantics
   - explicit expert redistribution across rows
   - final TP reduction

If there is a tradeoff between matching plain tensor shapes vs matching runtime behavior, prioritize runtime behavior for decode batch 128 on 4x8, because that is where tt-metal differs the most from a simple 1x8 TP-only implementation.